esents the first comprehensive overview of how Native American societies responded to climate variations over seven centuries. He describes how, as in Europe, the MWP ushered in a cultural renaissance, during which population levels surged and Native peoples substantially intensified agriculture, constructed monumental architecture, and produced sophisticated works of art. Foster follows the rise of three dominant cultural centers—Chaco Canyon in New Mexico, Cahokia on the middle Mississippi River, and Casas Grandes in northwestern Chihuahua, Mexico—that reached population levels comparable to those of London and Paris. Then he shows how the LIA reversed the gains of the MWP as population levels and agricultural production sharply declined; Chaco Canyon, Cahokia, and Casas Grandes collapsed; and dozens of smaller villages also collapsed or became fortresses.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCahokia Mounds State Historic Park (Ill.). 0aCasas Grandes culture -- Mexico -- Chihuahua (State). 0aCasas Grandes culturezMexicozChihuahua (State) 0aChaco culture -- New Mexico -- Chaco Canyon. 0aChaco culturezNew MexicozChaco Canyon. 0aIndigenous peoples -- Ecology -- Mexico. 0aIndigenous peoples -- Ecology -- North America. 0aIndigenous peoplesxEcologyzMexico. 0aIndigenous peoplesxEcologyzNorth America. 0aMississippian culture -- Illinois -- American Bottom. 0aMississippian culturezIllinoiszAmerican Bottom. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/73741940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292737426423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292737426/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  a